  "text": "SESSION ANALYSIS OF /tmp/session-summary.jsonl\n\nRaw data breakdown:\n- 89 total entries (user messages + assistant turns)\n- Session duration: ~1 hour (16:12 to 17:17)\n- Primary focus: Lazygit keybinding customization\n- File edits: 4 Edit operations recorded\n- Reads: 1 explicit file read of lazygit config\n- Web fetches: 3 WebFetch calls to lazygit docs\n\nKey inefficiency patterns identified:\n\n1. WRONG PATH TAKEN - Lines 21-47: Attempted to remap <space> to goInto in files context, then universal, then disabled default select mapping. This was completely reverted in line 54-57. Wasted ~8 turns trying context-based customization that lazygit doesn't support well.\n\n2. REPEATED MISTAKE - Lines 39-74: Multiple WebFetch calls checking keybindings without fully understanding lazygit's architecture first. Asked about f, then <tab>, then ;  without a systematic audit of what's available.\n\n3. ASSUMPTION WITHOUT VERIFICATION - Line 52: Suggested 'l' without checking if it was already mapped to panel navigation. User had to correct this.\n\n4. MISSING DOCUMENTATION - Lines 48-50: User had to read lazygit docs to understand keybinding system limitations. This knowledge should have been in CLAUDE.md or a skill before attempting edits.\n\n5. UNNECESSARY TOOL CALLS - Lines 39-74: Made 3 separate WebFetch calls when one comprehensive check of the default keybindings doc would have answered all questions. Context checking was reactive rather than proactive.\n\nToken cost estimate:\n- 6 failed WebFetch calls + explanations: ~2000 tokens\n- 3 Edit reversions: ~600 tokens  \n- 4 additional assistant turns explaining wrong paths: ~800 tokens\n- Total waste: ~3400 tokens (roughly 25% of session)",
